      "slug": "bryce-grad-school-1",
      "status": "publish",
      "type": "page",
      "link": "https://img.faculty.unlv.edu/lab/newsletter/issue-15/bryce-grad-school-1/",
      "title": {
        "rendered": "Bryce Grad School"
      },
      "content": {
        "rendered": "<style> .bryce { padding: 0 10px 0 0; } </style>\n<p><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"http://img.faculty.unlv.edu/lab/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/psychology-header-IMG-6.jpg\" alt=\"Header\" width=\"814\" height=\"170\"></p>\n<table border=\"0\" width=\"814\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td height=\"130\">\n<h1>Bryce Robinson</h1>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<table border=\"0\" width=\"814\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td height=\"10\">\n<p class=\"body\"><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"bryce\" src=\"http://img.faculty.unlv.edu/lab/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Bryce-Robinson-Spotlight-Author-Photo-scaled.jpg\" alt=\"bryce\" width=\"278\" height=\"370\" align=\"left\" hspace=\"0\" vspace=\"0\">Bryce Robinson undoubtedly had a fruitful and eventful undergraduate career: He conducted and presented research in two labs, excelled in multiple leadership roles, interned at a private practice, and won two prestigious awards. Consequently, his efforts earned him a coveted spot in the Counseling Psychology PhD program at Texas Tech!</p>\n<p class=\"body\">Bryce joined the Interactive Measurement Group in the spring of 2019. During his time in our lab, he gained valuable research experience and fulfilled many leadership roles. He co-authored four research posters, which he presented at six conferences, including the American Association for Behavioral Sciences, the Rocky Mountain Psychological Association, and the Western Psychological Association. He also led several workshops and took on leadership roles, such as Poster Leader, Conference Coordinator, and Interactive Mentoring Program Coordinator.</p>\n<p class=\"body\">Outside of the Interactive Measurement Group, Bryce worked with Dr. Shane Kraus as a research assistant for the Behavioral Addictions Lab. In this lab, he conducted research on the associations between PTSD and mental health correlates in a national survey of U.S. veterans. He is listed as first author on this research and plans to submit the manuscript for publication. As the son of a U.S. veteran, he seeks to have a positive impact on the lives of those who serve in our military. This desire underpins his overarching research goals aimed at informing policy decisions, resource allocation, screening, and treatment efforts for U.S. veterans.</p>\n<p class=\"body\">In addition to Bryce’s research accomplishments, he also completed an internship at a clinical private practice and joined many professional organizations. During his internship, he performed administrative tasks, observed clinical diagnostic intakes and client assessments, and learned how to score and interpret the Minnesota Multiphasic Personality Inventory. Bryce was also an active member of UNLV’s McNair Scholars Institute, the UNLV Outreach Undergraduate Mentorship Program, UNLV’s Psychology Club, and the Nevada Psychological Association.</p>\n<p class=\"body\">In the spring of 2021, Bryce graduated with his bachelor’s degree in Psychology and minor in Sociology.  Bryce’s strong work ethic and unwavering determination earned him the Outstanding Psychology Senior Award from the Department of Psychology and the Shining Star Award from the Outreach Undergraduate Mentoring Program.</p>\n<p class=\"body\">This fall, Bryce will be attending Texas Tech’s Counseling Psychology Ph.D. Program. At Texas Tech, he plans to work on advancing evidence-based assessment and understanding barriers to engagement and retention in mental health services – focusing on military and trauma-exposed populations.</p>\n<p class=\"body\">We look forward to seeing his future accomplishments. Congratulations, Bryce!</p>\n<hr size=\"15\">\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n",
        "protected": false
      },
